(482, 1, '2023-09-26 17:16:12', '2023-09-26 13:16:12', '<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"alignwide\"} -->\n<p class=\"alignwide\"><em><strong>TL;DR:</strong> Particulate matter is microscopic, thus capable of penetrating deep into our lungs and bloodstream, causing damage to our bodies. While there are other kinds of air pollution, such as ground-level ozone, nitrogen dioxide... this article focuses on particulate matter as it poses the most significant threat to our health.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<section class=\"alignfull\" id=\"explanation\" style=\"margin:0;padding:0; color:white\">\n            <div class=\"container\">\n                \n                <div class=\"row\">\n                    <div class=\"col-lg-6\">\n<h2>1. Microscopic Size\n</h2>\n                        <p>\n                            Particulate matter (PM) consists of microscopic particles small enough to be suspended in the air for a long period of time. Depends on the size of the particles, particulate matter can be further broken down to: PM10 (coarse particles less than 10 micrometers across) and PM2.5 (very fine particles less than 2.5 micrometers across). PM2.5 particles are often the direct result of human-made activities, such as coal and diesel burning, vehicle emission, construction site, and agriculture waste combustion.\n                        </p>\n<h2>2. Microscopic Comparison\n</h2>\n                        <p>\n                            Tiny as they are, PM2.5 particles are invisible to our naked eyes. The background of this page is an image of a single human hair magnified 1,000 - 10,000 times depending on your screen size. Scroll down to see how particulate matter compares.\n                        </p>\n\n                    </div>\n                </div>\n\n                <div class=\"items\">\n                    <div class=\"item-wrapper aligncenter\">\n                        <h4>\n                            Human hair<br>50 µm (0.05 mm)\n                        </h4>\n\n                    </div>\n                    <div class=\"item-wrapper aligncenter\">\n                        <img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nguyenvince/visualizing-pm2.5-pollution/main/assets/coarse-particle.png\" class=\"img-fluid\">\n                        <h4>\n                            Coarse particle PM10<br>10 µm\n                        </h4>\n\n                    </div>\n                    <div class=\"item-wrapper aligncenter\">\n                        <img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nguyenvince/visualizing-pm2.5-pollution/main/assets/red-blood-cell.png\" class=\"img-fluid\">\n                        <h4>\n                            Red blood cell<br>7 µm\n                        </h4>\n\n                    </div>\n                    <div class=\"item-wrapper aligncenter\">\n                        <img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nguyenvince/visualizing-pm2.5-pollution/main/assets/fine-particle.png\" class=\"img-fluid\">\n                        <h4>\n                            Fine particle PM2.5<br>&lt;2.5 µm\n                        </h4>\n\n                    </div>\n                    <div class=\"item-wrapper aligncenter\">\n                        <img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nguyenvince/visualizing-pm2.5-pollution/main/assets/coronavirus.png\" class=\"img-fluid\">\n                        <h4>\n                            Coronavirus<br>0.1 µm\n                        </h4>\n\n                    </div>\n                </div>\n\n                <div class=\"row\">\n                    <div class=\"col-lg-6\">\n<h2>3. Microscopic Killer\n</h2>\n                        <p style=\"padding-bottom: 0;\">\n                            As we can see, particulate matter, especially PM2.5 particles, is on the same size magnitude of our cells. Because of this, they can bypass our first line of defense mechanism, such as nasal hairs and mucus. PM2.5 are capable of penetrating deep into our alveoli (tiny air sacks that line the lungs), from which they find their ways into our bloodstream and into other organs, such as the brain, liver, and kidney. As some of their chemical compositions include heavy metals and toxins from anthropogenic activities, they are capable of causing inflammation, oxidative stress, blockage, and ultimately cancer. Acute symptoms such as coughing, sore throat, and breathing difficulty can also occur when exposed to high levels of particulate matter.\n                        </p>\n                    </div>\n                </div>\n\n            </div>\n\n        </section>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator {\"opacity\":\"css\",\"className\":\"is-style-dots\"} -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-css-opacity is-style-dots\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"textAlign\":\"right\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading has-text-align-right\">Next Articles</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"textAlign\":\"right\",\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading has-text-align-right\"><a href=\"/particulate-matter-in-abu-dhabi\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"../particulate-matter-in-abu-dhabi\">2. Particulate matter in Abu Dhabi</a></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"textAlign\":\"right\",\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading has-text-align-right\"><a href=\"/ways-to-protect-yourself\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"../ways-to-protect-yourself\">3. Ways to protect yourself</a></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'What is Particulate Matter', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '110-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-09-26 17:16:12', '2023-09-26 13:16:12', '', 110, 'https://blog.citiesair.com/?p=482', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
